'''Louis Hopewell Bauer''' [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] (July 18, 1888 - February 2 1964)<ref name="Books from 1947">{{cite web|url=http://www.kingkong.demon.co.uk/ccer/1947x.htm |title=Books from 1947 with US copyright not renewed |publisher=kingkong.demon.co.uk |accessdate=2009-06-15}}</ref><ref name="Louis H. Bauer: his continuing legacy">{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/12136070_Louis_H._Bauer_M.D._and_the_first_civil_U.S._aeromedical_standards_his_continuing_legacy |title=Louis H. Bauer, M.D., and the first civil U.S. aeromedical standards: his continuing legacy |last=Mohler |first=S R |accessdate=2009-06-14}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] doctor who founded the [[Aerospace Medical Association]] in 1929.<ref name=AsMA>{{cite web |url=http://www.asma.org/index.php |title=About the AsMA |author=Aerospace Medical Association |accessdate=2008-06-05 }}</ref> Dr. Bauer was the first medical director of the Aeronautics Branch of the [[United States Department of Commerce|Department of Commerce]] which became the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA).

== Career ==

He was [[Commandant]] of the [[School of Aviation Medicine]] between 1919 and 1925. During 1926, he established a medical section in the [[Bureau of Air Commerce]], [[Department of Commerce]]. On October 7, 1929, the [[Aero Medical Association of the United States]] was founded by Bauer.<ref name="Aeronautics and Astronautics Chronology, 1925-1929">{{cite web|url=http://history.nasa.gov/Timeline/1925-29.html |title=Aeronautics and Astronautics Chronology, 1925-1929 |last=Emme |first=Eugene M. |date=1961 |work=Aeronautics and Astronautics: An American Chronology of Science and Technology in the Exploration of Space, 1915-1960 |publisher=Washington, DC: National Aeronautics and Space Administration |pages=19<U+2013>26 |accessdate=2009-06-15}}</ref>

He also founded the [[Journal of Aviation Medicine]], the predecessor of the present [[Aviation, Space, and Environmental Medicine journal]]. The first issue of this Journal was published in March, 1930.<ref name="Louis H. Bauer: his continuing legacy" /> Bauer was the Journal's editor for 25 years.<ref name="100th anniversary of his birth">{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/20100666_100th_anniversary_of_Dr._Louis_H._Bauer's_birth |title=100th anniversary of Dr. Louis H. Bauer's birth |coauthors=M A Hoffman, M E Rothert, B J Stegmann |publisher=Aviation, space, and environmental medicine |accessdate=2009-06-14}}</ref>

Bauer was [[President]] and [[Chairman]] of the [[American Medical Association]] and leader of the [[World Medical Association]].<ref name="Charles T. Bauer" />

== Personal life ==

He had a son [[Charles Theodore Bauer]], born on March 3, 1919, to his wife, Meredith Bauer, who was a social worker with the [[Massachusetts General Hospital]]. His son was [[Co-Founder]] and the previous [[Chairman]] of [[AIM Management Group]].<ref name="Charles T. Bauer">{{cite web|url=http://www.allbusiness.com/company-activities-management/company-structures/5664474-1.html |title=Charles T. Bauer: Co-Founder and Retired Chairman AIM Management Group |date=Monday, June 28, 2004 |publisher=Business Wire |accessdate=2009-06-15}}</ref>

== Louis Bauer Award ==

Louis Bauer Award is awarded by the [[Aerospace Medical Association]]. It is given in honour of Bauer, who was the founder of the AMA. It is awarded annually "for the most significant contribution in aerospace medicine".<ref name="2002 Award Winners of the AMA">{{cite web|url=http://www.sasma.szd.si/test4/english/honorary/ernsting/doc/cv.htm |title=2002 Award Winners of the Aerospace Medical Association |date=July 2002 |publisher=sasma.szd.si |accessdate=2009-06-14}}</ref>

